    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" resp="#JP">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><expan><abbr>Γ</abbr><ex>αι</ex></expan> · Ματρίνι
                    <lb n="2"/>Φηλικίων ·
                    <lb n="3"/><expan><abbr>χρη</abbr><ex>στὲ</ex></expan> · καὶ · <expan><abbr>ἄμε</abbr><ex>μπτε</ex></expan> · χαῖρε
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp><app><note>Text from autopsy</note></app></listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
                <p>Gaius Matrinius Felikion, worthy and blameless, farewell!</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" resp="#JP">
                <p>Φηλικίων presumably renders the Latin Felicianus. Although the inscription is in Greek, it is noteworthy that it employs a Latin vocative form for Matrinius (implicit therefore also for Gaius), as well as abbreviating the formulaic words χρηστὲ and ἄμεμπτε, according to the more normal practices of Latin inscriptions. Ferrua suggests that the letters are of the third century AD, but an earlier date also seems possible</p>
            </div>
